Arrays are the most fundamental data structure in computing. Every other structure — stacks, queues, hash maps, heaps — is either built on top of arrays or contrasted against them. Strings are character arrays with extra rules. Once you understand how contiguous memory works, the performance characteristics of arrays become obvious rather than memorised — and you will see why so many problems reduce to clever array manipulation.

What is an Array.

An array is a fixed-size, contiguous block of memory where every element is the same type and therefore the same size. Elements are stored one after another with no gaps between them.

This layout enables the key property of arrays: constant time random access. To find the element at any index, the processor computes its memory address with simple arithmetic — the base address plus the index multiplied by the element size. No searching, no pointer-chasing — just a single calculation. Whether the index is zero or ten million, that calculation takes the same number of steps.

Picture a row of identical numbered lockers in a corridor. You know the first locker is at position one hundred. Every locker is the same width — say, four units. To reach locker fifty, you go to position one hundred plus fifty times four. You do not walk past lockers one through forty-nine — you jump directly to the right spot. That is exactly how array indexing works.

Array Operations and Their Cost.

Reading or updating an element by index costs constant time — one address calculation and you are there.

Searching an unsorted array costs linear time in the worst case — you may have to inspect every element before finding the target or confirming it is absent. In a sorted array, binary search brings this down to logarithmic time by halving the search space at each step.

Inserting at the end of an array costs constant time on average — you just write to the next available slot. But inserting anywhere else — at the front or in the middle — requires shifting every element after the insertion point one position to the right to make room. In the worst case, inserting at the very front shifts every element, giving you linear time.

Deletion works the same way in reverse. Removing the last element is instant. Removing from the front or middle requires shifting the remaining elements left to close the gap — linear time again.

The key insight is that arrays pay for their constant-time access with expensive insertions and deletions in the middle. This trade-off is fundamental, and it drives many of the decisions you will make when choosing data structures.

Dynamic Arrays.

Python does not have a fixed-size array in its standard library. The built-in list is a dynamic array — it wraps a fixed-size array under the hood and automatically resizes when it runs out of space.

The growth strategy is called doubling. When the internal array is full and you append another element, Python allocates a new array roughly twice the size, copies all existing elements into it, and frees the old one. This copying is linear — it touches every element. But it happens so rarely, as the array doubles each time, that averaged over many appends the cost per operation works out to constant time. This is called amortised constant time.

The trade-off is memory. A dynamic array often holds more space than it currently needs, because it pre-allocates capacity in anticipation of future growth. Each element in a Python list is also a pointer to a heap object rather than a raw value, which means even a list of integers uses considerably more memory than a raw array of four-byte integers would.

Strings.

A string is a sequence of characters — conceptually a character array, but with one critical difference: strings are immutable in both Python and Kotlin. Once a string is created, it cannot be modified. Any operation that appears to change a string actually creates a brand new string in memory and leaves the original untouched.

Immutability has a practical consequence that catches many programmers off guard. Concatenating strings together with a plus sign inside a loop is a performance trap. Each iteration allocates a new string and copies all the characters accumulated so far. After n iterations you have copied one plus two plus three, all the way up to n characters. That total is proportional to n squared — quadratic time.

The correct approach is to collect all the pieces in a list and join them in a single operation at the end. Python's join method allocates one string of exactly the right size and fills it in one pass — linear time. Kotlin's StringBuilder works the same way, buffering characters internally and building the final string once when you call toString.

The rule is simple: if you are building a string inside a loop, never use plus. Collect parts and join once at the end.

Two-Dimensional Arrays.

A two-dimensional array is an array of arrays — rows and columns, like a spreadsheet or a grid. Accessing any element still takes constant time because each row is itself an array, and array access is always constant time.

Two-dimensional arrays appear constantly in data structures and algorithms problems — as grids for graph traversal, as tables for dynamic programming, and as matrices for mathematical computations.

One important trap in Python: if you create a two-dimensional grid by multiplying a row with the star operator and then multiplying that by a number of rows, you get a list of references all pointing to the same inner list. Modifying one row modifies every row because they are all the same object. The correct approach is to use a list comprehension that creates a fresh inner list for each row independently.

Common Array and String Patterns.

Two patterns come up in array and string problems more than almost any others.

The first is prefix sums. A prefix sum array stores the cumulative total at each position. You build it in a single pass — linear time — and once it exists, you can answer any range sum query in constant time. Instead of adding up all the elements between two indices every time, you subtract two values from the prefix array. This technique turns what would be repeated linear work into a one-time linear setup followed by constant-time queries.

The second is frequency counting. When you need to know how often each element appears — in an array of numbers or a string of characters — you make a single pass and tally counts. For lowercase letters specifically, a fixed-size array of twenty-six integers is faster and simpler than a hash map. The index for each character is computed by subtracting the character A from the current character, giving you a number from zero to twenty-five.

Key Takeaways.

Arrays store elements in contiguous memory. Index access is constant time because the address is arithmetic, not a search.

Insertion and deletion in the middle are linear time — elements must shift. At the end they are constant time on average.

Python lists are dynamic arrays that resize by doubling. The amortised append cost is constant time, but each element is a pointer to a heap object.

Strings are immutable in both Python and Kotlin. Building a string with plus in a loop is quadratic. Use join in Python or StringBuilder in Kotlin.

For two-dimensional arrays in Python, always use a list comprehension to initialise — never the star shortcut, which copies references instead of creating independent rows.

And the two most useful preprocessing patterns are prefix sums for range queries and frequency arrays for character or element counts.

In the next notebook we move to linked lists — a structure that trades array's constant-time index access for constant-time insertion and deletion anywhere in the list, using pointers instead of contiguous memory.
